              -mer RANKer) that combines several components, including a hierarchical selection strategy with adaptive size restrictions and an equitable coverage strategy. We implement KRANK in highly optimized code and combine it with the locality-sensitive-hashing classifier CONSULT-II to build a taxonomic classification and profiling method. On several benchmarks, KRANK
              k
              -mer selection dramatically reduces memory consumption with minimal loss in classification accuracy. We show in extensive analyses based on CAMI benchmarks that KRANK outperforms
              k
              -mer-based alternatives in terms of taxonomic profiling and comes close to the best marker-based methods in terms of accuracy.},
	language = {en},
	urldate = {2024-09-12},
